      "id": "9fb6cdc0feb85c93",
      "text": "As we move around Uganda, thoughts wander towards the meaning of this base, used with the first cohort of trained DiG Guides. The power of a two-word base is inextricably linked to the power of being asked to define the terms for ourselves. As we look around at those returning home after 50 years away, beginning with a forced exile, we wonder what might these two words mean to them. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8ff44cd9e36b7199",
      "text": "We are eating up the miles, or kilometres as distance is measured here. There is much talk of the next place that is coming, the memories held there, the anticipation of the new memories that might be created. There is a sense of collective sharing as we discover that there are many overlaps in place and time across all of the memories. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fa4e8c6728a3ce24",
      "text": "The emotions are raw, real, and for some, overwhelming. Reconnecting to those that have passed when seeing the homes that they lived in, the businesses they ran, the places that were given up for one reason or another. The reluctance to accept that things have changed, not always for the better, at times beyond recognition. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5e6990e45947694a",
      "text": "There are places that have remained the same. We notice that places of worship are places of comfort for the returning families. They hold a familiarity, stories of positive experiences and cause for celebration of the gatherings held there. Contributions were made then to create them and more donations offered today to maintain and sustain them. Each of them provide a sense of peace found in returning to the heart of home. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "21ed860abf4aca57",
      "text": "The other places that have remained the same are the schools. This is surprising in some ways, not so much in others. The population is young here, we have known this for some time. The presence of international human rights organisations is felt across the country. While there are still many young children sitting with parents during school hours to sell wares, break stones and other trades, there is, we are told, generally an expectation that children will go to school. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2478fff904fac7ed",
      "text": "The learning environments are the same. Returning to classrooms after fifty to sixty years and sitting on the benches, the family are easily able to recall where they sat, who with and the punishments given if they or their friends stepped out of line. The blackboards, the notebooks, the signs on the walls… all remain. This makes it easier for the family to reconnect to a sense of belonging here. To remember who they were and to celebrate who they have become. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "db207f6cb622c3b2",
      "text": "Yet the world around us is changing. As we continue on the [[Path of Transformation]], we are curious about how these feelings of belonging transfer to the next generation. We wonder how each person might live brightly, reaching their [[Infinite Potential]]. We dream of a world where everyone might live into [[Becoming Whole]]. "
    }
